{# ══ Activity 1 — Introduction ════════════════════════════════ #}

{% call activitySection(1, "What Are Modal Verbs?", "book") %}
<p>
  Modal verbs are a special group of auxiliary verbs that express <strong>attitude</strong>
  towards an action rather than describing the action itself. They do not change form
  (no <em>-s</em>, <em>-ed</em>, or <em>-ing</em>) and are always followed by a bare infinitive.
</p>
<p>The core English modals are:</p>
<p style="font-size:1.05rem; letter-spacing:0.05em; color:#ff8c00;">
  can &bull; could &bull; may &bull; might &bull; shall &bull; should &bull; will &bull; would &bull; must
</p>
<p>
  Each modal can express more than one meaning depending on context. In this unit we focus on
  four key functions: <strong>possibility</strong>, <strong>ability</strong>,
  <strong>obligation</strong>, and <strong>permission</strong>.
</p>
{% endcall %}


{# ══ Activity 2 — The Four Functions ════════════════════════  #}

{% call activitySection(2, "The Four Functions", "list-check") %}
<p class="mb-3">Expand each function to see which modals are used and when.</p>

<div class="accordion" id="unit02-functions">

  {% call accordion("acc-02-a", "Possibility — something that might happen or be true") %}
  <p><strong>Modals:</strong> <em>can, could, may, might</em></p>
  <table class="table table-sm table-dark table-bordered mt-2" style="font-size:0.875rem;">
    <thead><tr><th>Time</th><th>Example</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Past</td><td>She <strong>could</strong> have missed the bus.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Present</td><td>It <strong>may</strong> rain later.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Future</td><td>We <strong>might</strong> visit Tokyo next year.</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  {% endcall %}

  {% call accordion("acc-02-b", "Ability — what someone is capable of doing") %}
  <p><strong>Modals:</strong> <em>can, could, be able to</em></p>
  <table class="table table-sm table-dark table-bordered mt-2" style="font-size:0.875rem;">
    <thead><tr><th>Time</th><th>Example</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Past</td><td>He <strong>could</strong> swim when he was five.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Present</td><td>She <strong>can</strong> speak three languages.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Future</td><td>They <strong>will be able to</strong> join us next week.</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  {% endcall %}

  {% call accordion("acc-02-c", "Obligation — what someone is required to do") %}
  <p><strong>Modals:</strong> <em>must, should, shall, have to</em></p>
  <table class="table table-sm table-dark table-bordered mt-2" style="font-size:0.875rem;">
    <thead><tr><th>Time</th><th>Example</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Past</td><td>You <strong>should</strong> have called first.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Present</td><td>Students <strong>must</strong> submit their work by Friday.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Future</td><td>Everyone <strong>will have to</strong> register in advance.</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  {% endcall %}

  {% call accordion("acc-02-d", "Permission — what someone is allowed to do") %}
  <p><strong>Modals:</strong> <em>can, could, may, might</em></p>
  <table class="table table-sm table-dark table-bordered mt-2" style="font-size:0.875rem;">
    <thead><tr><th>Time</th><th>Example</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Past</td><td>Students <strong>might</strong> use dictionaries in old exams.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Present</td><td>You <strong>may</strong> leave early today.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Future</td><td>Members <strong>may</strong> bring one guest next term.</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  {% endcall %}

</div>
{% endcall %}


